As you probably know, Voltaire is not railing against Nature so much as he is against the Leibnizian theodicy (and rationalist deism) of his time that asserted that most suffering and all evil in the world w  as a product of humans and their free will, and that it was necessary for the Creator to give humans free will so that they could choose their destiny.  God, according to Leibniz, like a rational mathematician, created a universe which minimized human suffering, while preserving free will.
Voltaire thought that the Lisbon earthquake, with its extremes of death and destruction clearly created by Nature and Nature's God, should put the final nail in the coffin of such thinking.
However, Voltaire himself was attracted to aspects of deism again and again.

